title: CROSS COUNTRY: Rappahannock County's Wood, Jenkins defend Bull Run titles
text: by Ronald Counts Julia Wood has, far and away, cemented her place as the greatest girls cross country runner to ever hit the trail at Rappahannock County High School. If her senior season continues trending the way it is, she'll finish her career as one of the best runners the state has ever produced. Already the two-time 1A defending state champion, Wood claimed her fourth straight Bull District District title Wednesday with a time of 18:18. Wood also finished sixth out of about 350 varsity girls in the A race Sept. 19 at the Oatlands Invitational. Wood claimed the 2013 1A state title with an 18:47, and last season's state crown in 18:58. She also owns five spring track and field state championships after winning her third straight 1,600-meter title last season with a time of 5:26. Rappahannock County's Gavin Jenkins also won his second straight Bull Run District title Wednesday with a time of 16:15. Jenkins is also a two-time Conference 43 champion, won the 1A East title last season and finished sixth at the 1A state meet with a 16:55. The Panthers' Jacklyn Humphries finished 28th in the girls Bull Run race in 22:06. Savannah Hensley took 35th in 23:07, and Camryn Clark finished 36th in 23:08. Sam Barnes finished 22nd in the boys race in 18:11. » EASTERN VIEW The Cyclones placed six runners in the top 20 Wednesday during the Fredericksburg All-Area Meet at Fredericksburg Christian School. Sophomore Nate Cotter powered the boys to a third-place finish out of 14 teams, taking fourth overall with a time of 16:49. Philip Grotz finished 10th in 17:08.5, and Mitchell Luckinbill took 11th in 17:08.6. Dom Pressley finished 26th in 18:01, and Matt LaRosa took 42nd in 18:32. Eighth-grader Blake Sheads finished 12th in 19:29, but his score didn't count. Freshman Kirstyn Gilyard paced the girls to a fifth-place finish out of 12 teams, taking sixth overall in 20:21. Erin LaSalle finished 14th in 21:25, and Jessie Ritz took 19th in 21:42. Hope Young finished 44th in 23:00, and Raegan Baker finished 61st in 23:45. » CULPEPER COUNTY Kellie Hyde led Culpeper County Wednesday at the Fredericksburg All-Area Meet, finishing 11th overall in a time of 20:58. Tatum Jacobs finished 19th in 24:35, Amaya Webb finished 44th in 27:14 and Bri Csontos took 60th in 23:41. As a team, Culpeper's girls finished ninth. Tony Verardo led Culpeper's boys, finishing 39th in 18:26. Jacob Hardaway took 45th in 18:40. As a team, the boys finished 10th. » MADISON COUNTY Ben Dillon led Madison's boys Wednesday at the Bull Run District meet, finishing 28th in 18:31. Zach McLearen finished 33rd in 18:48. Kimberly Carpenter led Madison's girls at the Bull Run meet, finishing 29th in 22:13. Ashley Sharp finished 38th in 23:21, and Katelyn Rider took 39th in 23:27.
